<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-536-511  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 536 511.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Business  Oct 15 1990 v16 n19 p25(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The Baldrige Award can make you a winner even without winning.andO;(DEC is an example)(Update: Commentary) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Socolovsky, Alberto.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A company can benefit by its quality efforts even if it does notwin the Malcolm Baldrige National Quality Award, as exemplified bythe impact of DEC's quality initiatives.andP;  Over 45,000 employees(over one-third of the firm's workforce) have participated inDEC's quality-education program since 1986.andP;  DEC developed fourmajor quality initiatives: 'voice of the customer, best-in-classbenchmarking, six-sigma performance and cycle time.' Impacts ofthese activities include a reduction of warranty expenses from1985's five percent of net operating revenue to 2.6 percent in1988; decrease in scrap as a percentage of gross inventory from1986's 39 percent to 26 percent in 1987; halving the developmentcycle times for low-end systems; and a doubling of mean timebetween failure for DEC's RA-90 1.2Gbyte hard disk over theprevious RA-82.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Digital Equipment Corp. (quality control).andO;Ticker:    DEC.andO;Topic:     Performance ImprovementAchievements and AwardsMethodsCompany ProfileManufacturersMalcolm Baldrige National Quality AwardQuality controlComputer industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>